## Target Persona (Ideal Reader)

**Primary**: Senior AI tech leads (3-8 years experience) who:
- are building AI empowered products and services, want to learn from the best practices and mistakes
- are seeking the guidance and advice from the experts, wanted some blueprint to follow
- are managing and leading AI engineers native teams, want to improve their leadership skills
- are looking for practical insights they can apply to their own work
- they understand the AI and engineering,
- who connects the engineering with business needs
- works in enterprise environments, knows the problems and challenges in those environments: bureaucracy, politics, culture, etc.
- CTO, VP of Engineering, Director of AI, Head of AI, etc.

**Secondary**: AI engineers, AI product mangerer who works with AI tech leaders, who: 
- are challendbed by the stakeholders expectations,
- who have enough the unrealistic deadlines and requirements,
- who belive that AI could help, but at the same time they understand that we all needs to  learn, make mistakes and improve.
- who want to hear the honest and transparent insights from the the field, not just the wins, but also the failures and negative results.
- who seek some assurance that they are on the right track, and they are not alone in this journey.


**What they value**: curiosity, technical leadership, honesty over hype, open science, contrarian but evidence-backed opinions.


## Topics to Lean Into
- Agentic systems, multi-agent systems, MCP, LLM engineering, Voice AI, Concept Encoder, etc.
- Architecture innovation (attention alternatives, concept learning, efficient encoders)
- Voice and language models for conversational tutoring, speech-to-speech models
- Paper analysis with personal commentary and connection to own research
- Efficiency and sustainability in AI (compute-aware research)
- Open science, reproducibility, research methodology

## Topics to Avoid
- Generic AI hype or "AI will replace X" takes
- Listicles without substance
- Prompt engineering tips (unless deeply technical)
- Content without personal experience or data backing it
- Hot takes on AI safety/alignment without technical grounding
- Anything that sounds like marketing copy

## Platform-Specific Persona
- **Blog**: Most technical, longest form. The "lab notebook made public."
- **LinkedIn**: Professional but personal. The "thoughtful colleague sharing over coffee."
- **X**: Most concise and punchy. The "researcher at a conference poster session."
